"""
mkt-christ: Ezekiel 41–43 (73 verses)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-ezekiel-41-43.py

Ch41: temple interior measurements and carved cherubim/palms
Ch42: priests' chambers and the 500×500 sacred boundary
Ch43: return of the glory through the east gate; altar consecration

Interpretation decisions:
- The two-faced cherubim (man + lion, 41:19) read as Lion of Judah / Son of Man — both faces of the one Christ
- The wooden altar called "table before the LORD" (41:22) = Christological altar/table
- East gate (43:1-4) connected to Triumphal Entry and Parousia
- Ariel/altar horns (43:15-16) as the four-cornered reach of atonement
- Seven-day consecration (43:25-26) = the Passion Week; eighth day (43:27) = the Resurrection
- Christ burned "outside the gate" (Heb 13:12) as fulfillment of the sin offering burned outside the sanctuary (43:21)
"""

import json, pathlib
ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

EZEKIEL_CHRIST = {
    "41": {
        "1": "<p>The angelic guide brings Ezekiel into the nave (היכל, the Holy Place) and measures its entrance posts. Jesus identifies himself as the true temple: 'Destroy this temple, and in three days I will raise it up' (John 2:19-21). The nave that Ezekiel enters by precise measurement is the sanctuary whose greater fulfillment is Christ's body — every dimension pointing toward the one in whom 'the whole fullness of deity dwells bodily' (Col 2:9).</p>",
        "2": "<p>The nave door opening is 40 cubits long and 20 cubits wide. Forty is the dimension of the Holy Place and the number of probationary testing: forty days in the wilderness (Matt 4:2), forty years of desert wandering. Christ endured the forty-day wilderness ordeal and so fills the Holy Place with an obedience that Israel's desert generation could never achieve — entering not a sanctuary made with hands but heaven itself (Heb 9:24).</p>",
        "3": "<p>The inner room (the Most Holy Place, קדש הקדשים) has a six-cubit-wide doorway, seven cubits tall. Hebrews 9:7 notes that only the high priest entered the Most Holy Place once a year, 'not without taking blood.' Christ entered 'the greater and more perfect tabernacle not made with hands' by his own blood, securing an eternal redemption (Heb 9:11-12) — the restrictive door of the Most Holy Place flung wide by his sacrifice.</p>",
        "4": "<p>The Most Holy Place measured twenty cubits square: 'This is the Most Holy Place.' A twenty-by-twenty square plan mirrors the cubic perfection of the heavenly city: the new Jerusalem is 12,000 stadia in length, width, and height — a colossal cube (Rev 21:16). The shape of the Most Holy Place is the shape of the whole new creation, because Christ's indwelling presence makes every inch of the new cosmos holy to its core.</p>",
        "5": "<p>The wall of the house and the side chambers built against it. The Hebrew for side chamber (צלע, <em>tsela</em>) is the same word used for Adam's 'rib' from which Eve was formed (Gen 2:21-22). The church is built from the side of the second Adam: John 19:34 records water and blood flowing from Christ's pierced side, and patristic reading sees in this the sacraments (baptism and Eucharist) — the birth of the bride of Christ from his wounded side.</p>",
        "6": "<p>The side chambers built in three stories. The threefold vertical ordering of the temple (forecourt, holy place, most holy place) mirrors the threefold structure of all access to God: the outer court open to all Israel, the inner court for priests, the Holy of Holies for the high priest alone. In Christ all three levels of the approach to God are fulfilled and democratized: 'we have confidence to enter the holy places by the blood of Jesus' (Heb 10:19) — all believers now hold high-priestly access.</p>",
        "7": "<p>The winding staircase ascending through the three stories. The ascending structure of the temple connects to Jacob's ladder (Gen 28:12), which Jesus applies to himself: 'You will see heaven opened, and the angels of God ascending and descending on the Son of Man' (John 1:51). Christ is the winding way of ascent from the ground floor of human life to the highest floor of divine presence.</p>",
        "8": "<p>The platform/foundation of the side chambers measured a full reed of six cubits. Paul declares: 'No one can lay a foundation other than that which is laid, which is Jesus Christ' (1 Cor 3:11). Every chamber in the temple complex rests on a foundation of divine precision — the architectural image of the church built on and secure in the one foundation who is Christ.</p>",
        "9": "<p>The outer wall of the side chambers, five cubits thick. Five is associated with grace and Torah: the five books of Moses, the fivefold ministry (Eph 4:11). The five-cubit outer wall serves as the protective boundary of the holy side chambers — the law as the outer protective structure that guards the sanctuary of Christ's body, now fulfilled in him who said 'I have not come to abolish the law but to fulfill it' (Matt 5:17).</p>",
        "10": "<p>A twenty-cubit gap between the temple chambers and the priests' chambers on every side. Twenty cubits is the width of the Most Holy Place. This maintained distance echoes the reverential space preserved around the divine presence — the holy distance that becomes free approach in Christ. Heb 4:16: 'Let us then with confidence draw near to the throne of grace.' The gap is bridged not by removing holiness but by the great high priest who stands within the gap for us.</p>",
        "11": "<p>Doors of the side chambers opening north and south. The north-south orientation — the two remaining cardinal directions after east (the glory's entrance) and west (the separate building) — suggests that access to the rooms of God's temple community opens in all directions. The priestly community's doors face universally, as the church's mission: 'make disciples of all nations' (Matt 28:19), the chambers of Christ's body open on every side.</p>",
        "12": "<p>The separate building (גִּזְרָה) at the western end, facing away from the east. The west is the direction of the nations who have not yet turned toward the eastern glory. This building's presence in the template complex anticipates the inclusion of those yet outside: Eph 2:13 — 'But now in Christ Jesus you who once were far off have been brought near by the blood of Christ.' The western separate space becomes integrated into the holy district in the new Jerusalem, where there is no more separation between sacred and profane.</p>",
        "13": "<p>Total length of the house: 100 cubits. A hundred is the number of completion in Scripture: Abraham's son born at 100 years (Gen 21:5), the parable of the hundredfold harvest (Mark 4:8), the ninety-nine left to seek the one lost (Luke 15:4). The temple at 100 cubits reaches its full measure. Paul prays that believers be 'filled with all the fullness of God' (Eph 3:19) — the complete measure of the temple met in the stature of Christ.</p>",
        "14": "<p>The east face of the temple: 100 cubits wide. The east face receives the returning glory (ch. 43). The east orientation of the temple's full extent is the face the risen Christ turns toward the world at the dawn of resurrection: he who 'came from the east' (Matt 24:27) and through whom 'the glory of the LORD filled the house' (43:5) displays himself in all his full measure to the watching creation.</p>",
        "15": "<p>The length of the building behind the temple and its galleries. The complete measurement of all the architectural elements. Christ's salvation is not partial or provisional — it accounts for every dimension of the human need for God. John 19:30: 'It is finished.' The entire floor plan is complete; not a single cubit is missing from the atoning work of Christ.</p>",
        "16": "<p>The inner decorations: latticed windows, galleries on three sides. The latticed windows admit light without full exposure — they are windows of revelation, seeing without being overwhelmed. Jesus is the light of the world (John 8:12), but the latticed window of Scripture mediates his glory so that we can perceive it without being consumed. The three-sided galleries = the threefold witness: Father, Son, and Spirit (1 John 5:7-8).</p>",
        "17": "<p>Measured above and around the inner house. The divine dimensions cover every surface, interior and exterior. Christ's salvation is comprehensive: there is no dimension of human life or cosmic reality that stands outside the scope of his redemptive measurement. Eph 3:18: 'the breadth and length and height and depth' of the love of Christ surpasses all measurement while being measurable by the Spirit.</p>",
        "18": "<p>The interior walls are covered with alternating cherubim and palm trees. The cherubim (Gen 3:24) were placed to guard the way to the tree of life after the fall; here they alternate with palm branches inside the restored sanctuary — suggesting their guardianship role is now transformed to celebratory presence. Rev 2:7: 'To the one who conquers I will grant to eat of the tree of life, which is in the paradise of God.' Christ's victory gives access to the tree the cherubim once guarded.</p>",
        "19": "<p>Each cherub has two faces: the face of a man and the face of a young lion. The dual-faced cherubim are the Christological images of the temple's interior: the face of a man points to the Son of Man (Dan 7:13; John 5:27), the incarnate mediator who is 'bone of our bone'; the face of a lion points to the Lion of the tribe of Judah (Rev 5:5), the conquering King. Christ's two natures — fully human, fully royal-divine — are declared on the walls of his sanctuary. The palms between them are the branches of his triumphal entry (John 12:13) and the palms of his redeemed (Rev 7:9).</p>",
        "20": "<p>From the floor to above the doorway, cherubim and palm trees covered the nave wall. Floor to ceiling, entrance to interior — the entire space of Christ's sanctuary declares his dual identity and his victorious welcome. The sanctuary itself is a visual sermon: everywhere you look within the body of Christ you see the Lion-Man who entered Jerusalem to palm-branches and who now reigns. The church's whole interior life is shaped by this double vision of Christ.</p>",
        "21": "<p>The doorposts of the nave were square (foursquare). Square doorposts signal perfect stability and symmetry — the fourfold completeness that runs through Scripture (four directions, four creatures, fourfold Gospel, four-square city). The entrance into the holy place through Christ is perfectly balanced: neither too narrow for sinners nor too wide for holiness. He is 'the door' (John 10:9) whose foursquare frame admits the lost and maintains the sacred.</p>",
        "22": "<p>The wooden altar, three cubits high and two cubits square: 'This is the table that stands before the LORD.' The altar is identified as the table — the place of the bread of presence. Three cubits high (the three days of resurrection), two cubits square (the two natures of Christ), and made of wood (the material of the cross). Paul writes: 'We have an altar from which those who serve the tent have no right to eat' (Heb 13:10). The wooden table-altar before the LORD is the Eucharistic table: Christ who is the altar is also the bread, the one sacrifice and the holy food, offered and shared in the same act.</p>",
        "23": "<p>Double doors for the nave and for the inner sanctuary. The doubled doors suggest paired access points into God's presence. Hebrews 10:19-20 speaks of 'the new and living way that he opened for us through the curtain, that is, through his flesh.' The two-ply door — outer and inner — corresponds to the outer sacrifice at the cross (the visible, public act of atonement) and the inner intercession in the heavenly sanctuary (the ongoing high-priestly work within the veil).</p>",
        "24": "<p>Each door had two swinging leaves. Four leaves total for the two doors — folding open to create full access. Isaiah 45:1 speaks of doors opened before Cyrus; Revelation 3:8 promises Philadelphia 'an open door.' The swinging leaves of the inner sanctuary's double doors fold fully back, removing every barrier, when Christ's atonement is applied. Eph 2:18: 'through him we both have access in one Spirit to the Father' — both leaves open wide.</p>",
        "25": "<p>Cherubim and palm trees decorated the doors of the nave, as on the walls. The door bears the same imagery as the interior — Christ who is the door (John 10:9) carries on his own person the marks of the sanctuary's décor: the human-lion dual nature and the palms of his victory. The entrance point and the interior are continuous; there is no bait-and-switch from an attractive door to a different interior. What you see at the door — the Lion-Man with palms — is what fills the entire house.</p>",
        "26": "<p>Latticed windows and palm trees on both sides of the porch. The porch (אולם, <em>ulam</em>) is the outer face of the temple, the threshold where approach meets arrival. Latticed windows admit selective light; palm trees announce victory; thick beams provide support on either side. The approach to Christ combines revelation (windows), triumph (palms), and strength (beams). Those who draw near find that the structure holding them as they enter is the very strength of Christ who 'is the same yesterday and today and forever' (Heb 13:8).</p>"
    },
    "42": {
        "1": "<p>The angelic guide leads Ezekiel north to the chambers opposite the separate place in the outer court. The priestly chambers beside the holy complex locate the ministers of the sanctuary in proximity to their work. Christ creates a priestly order permanently settled near the divine presence: 'You are a chosen race, a royal priesthood, a holy nation, a people for his own possession' (1 Pet 2:9). The church is not a visiting congregation but a resident priesthood.</p>",
        "2": "<p>The north chamber block: 100 cubits long and 50 cubits wide. The hundredfold length = complete; the fifty-cubit width corresponds to the Jubilee (year of release, Lev 25). The priestly chambers are both complete and Jubilary — the church's priestly residence is built on the dimensions of liberation. Christ proclaims 'the year of the LORD's favor' (Luke 4:19) and makes his priestly people permanent inhabitants of Jubilee.</p>",
        "3": "<p>The chambers face the twenty-cubit inner court and the pavement of the outer court. Situated between the inner court (near the Holy of Holies) and the outer court (open to more general access), the chambers occupy the mediating zone. Christ occupies this same mediating zone between God and humanity as the 'one mediator between God and men, the man Christ Jesus' (1 Tim 2:5) — exactly positioned at the intersection of the innermost holiness and the outer human court.</p>",
        "4": "<p>A one-cubit inner walk between the chambers, ten cubits wide. The inner walk of the priest through his own chambers — a private processional within the sanctuary complex. Christ has his own inner path: Heb 9:24 ('he entered not into holy places made with hands, a copy of the true things, but into heaven itself'). He also invites his priestly people to walk this inner way with him: 'Follow me' (John 1:43; 21:22) is the call to the priestly walk through the interior of his sanctuary.</p>",
        "5": "<p>The upper chambers were narrower than the lower because the galleries reduced the floor space at each story. The progression of narrowing toward the top — the closer to the divine presence, the more restricted the access — reflects the graduated holiness of the sacrificial system. Yet Christ inverts this narrowing: at the ascension he enters the narrowest holy place of all, the very throne of God, and then pours out the Spirit on all flesh (Acts 2:17), widening the access of God's presence from the uppermost point downward.</p>",
        "6": "<p>Three stories, without columns like the outer court, so the space was reduced from the lower and middle floors. The free-standing design of the priests' chambers — no borrowed support from outer-court pillars — mirrors the self-sufficient structure of the church's priestly life in Christ. Paul's letter to the Galatians insists that the Gentile church needs no pillars from Jerusalem (Gal 2:6): the structure of the new covenant priesthood stands on Christ alone, not on borrowed external supports.</p>",
        "7": "<p>An outer wall fifty cubits long alongside the chambers. The outer wall creates the boundary of the holy area. Fifty cubits again evokes the Jubilee measurement. The Jubilee boundary is the boundary of the church: not a wall that excludes but a marker of the space within which the year of the LORD's favor operates. All within this boundary — all who are in Christ — live under the Jubilee release.</p>",
        "8": "<p>The chambers in the outer court measured fifty cubits, while those facing the nave measured one hundred. The doubled length of the inner-facing chambers over the outer-court chambers marks the greater depth of what opens toward the holy place. Access toward Christ deepens proportionally: the closer the orientation to the nave (to Christ's body), the greater the depth of the dwelling place that opens up. 'Abide in me, and I in you' (John 15:4) — the depth of the chambers grows as orientation toward the vine increases.</p>",
        "9": "<p>The entrance to the chambers from the east, as one enters from the outer court. East-entry again — the glory's direction, Christ's direction. The priestly chambers are entered from the same direction as the coming glory (ch. 43). The church's priestly life is entered by turning toward Christ: baptism (Rom 6:3-4) is the east-facing entry into the priestly chambers of life in Christ.</p>",
        "10": "<p>Chambers along the south wall of the inner court, opposite the separate place. The southern positioning mirrors the northern chambers (v. 1-8), completing the bilateral layout. The church's priestly community surrounds the sanctuary on all sides — north and south. At Pentecost people from every direction of the compass heard the mighty works of God in their own language (Acts 2:9-11): the chambers of the priestly people of Christ open universally.</p>",
        "11": "<p>The south chambers matched the north in design and arrangement. Symmetry throughout the priestly complex. God's design for his priestly people has perfect bilateral symmetry: Jew and Gentile, male and female, slave and free — in Christ all are one (Gal 3:28), all assigned to the same symmetric chambers of the priestly complex, all with the same access, all serving through the same one mediator.</p>",
        "12": "<p>The entrance to the south chambers matching the north: access via the eastern wall. Both sets of chambers entered from the east, from the direction of the coming glory. The consistent east-entry enforces the consistent principle: all priestly access to God is through Christ, who comes from the east, who is the way. 'I am the way, and the truth, and the life; no one comes to the Father except through me' (John 14:6) — one direction of entry for every chamber.</p>",
        "13": "<p>'The north chambers and the south chambers which are opposite the separate place are the holy chambers where the priests who approach the LORD shall eat the most holy offerings — the sin offering, the grain offering, and the guilt offering.' The priests eat the most holy things in these chambers. Christ issues the same invitation to his royal priesthood: 'Unless you eat the flesh of the Son of Man and drink his blood, you have no life in you ... Whoever feeds on my flesh and drinks my blood abides in me, and I in him' (John 6:53, 56). The Eucharist is the priestly eating of the most holy offering in the chambers of the LORD's house — all three sacrifice-categories (sin, grain, guilt) fulfilled in the one holy food.</p>",
        "14": "<p>'When the priests enter, they shall not go out of the holy place into the outer court without laying there the garments in which they minister ... for these are holy.' The priestly vestment change at the holy-to-outer transition. Christ gives his priestly people a robe of righteousness (Isa 61:10) to wear in the holy place, and the garment of salvation for the outer court of daily life. The distinction between the two is not abolished but maintained: the holiness of the priestly act of worship is particular and specific, while the garment of the saved one is worn everywhere. Rev 7:14: 'They have washed their robes and made them white in the blood of the Lamb.'</p>",
        "15": "<p>'Now when he had finished measuring the interior of the temple area, he led me out by the gate that faced east.' The measuring of the interior concludes, and the exit is through the east gate — the gate of the returning glory. The priestly tour of the inner courts ends where the Christological drama peaks: at the east gate, the gate through which Christ returns. The whole interior is measured and understood only in relation to the east-gate event — the coming of the glory that fills it.</p>",
        "16": "<p>The east side measured with the reed: 500 reeds. The measuring reed is six cubits (40:5), so 500 reeds = 3,000 cubits. The fourfold 500-reed measurement creates a vast 1.5-kilometer-square enclosure. The scale of the sacred boundary exceeds any human city — Ezekiel's temple complex describes not a building but a transformed geography. The new Jerusalem scales this further: 12,000 stadia on each side (Rev 21:16), the whole city a Holy of Holies. All geography is consecrated in Christ.</p>",
        "17": "<p>The north side measured 500 reeds. The four equal sides — north, south, east, west — describe a perfect square. The temple district is the new creation's basic shape: foursquare, comprehensive, equal in all directions. The gospel goes to the four corners (Matt 28:19), and the result is a priestly community that is perfectly square — no corner neglected, no direction privileged. The fourfold equal measurement of the sacred district is the spatial form of Christ's universal dominion.</p>",
        "18": "<p>The south side measured 500 reeds. South is the direction of the nations in the OT cosmology (Arabia, Egypt). The 500 southern reeds include the nations in the sacred district's measurement. Paul's mission to the south and west (and beyond) is the measurement of Christ's foursquare dominion extending to the previously unconsecrated south: 'There is neither Jew nor Greek, there is neither slave nor free' (Gal 3:28) — all four cardinal peoples within the 500-cubit sacred square.</p>",
        "19": "<p>He turned about to the west side and measured 500 reeds. West = the direction of the nations, the sunset lands, the sea. Ezekiel's vision encompasses west as fully as east: no direction is excluded from the 500-reed measurement. The gospel's westward march (Acts 16:9, the Macedonian call; Rom 15:24, the planned mission to Spain) fulfills the westward reach of the sacred square. The setting sun's direction is claimed for the LORD's holy district.</p>",
        "20": "<p>'It had a wall around it, 500 cubits long and 500 cubits broad, to make a separation between the holy and the common.' The enclosing wall that separates holy from common. Ephesians 2:14: 'For he himself is our peace, who has made us both one and has broken down in his flesh the dividing wall of hostility.' Christ breaks down the dividing wall between Jew and Gentile — but the wall of separation between the holy and the common is not destroyed; it is redrawn. The new boundary is Christ's atoning blood, which makes holy those who were common (1 Pet 2:10: 'Once you were not a people, but now you are God's people') and excludes whatever remains unclean (Rev 21:27).</p>"
    },
    "43": {
        "1": "<p>The angelic guide brings Ezekiel to the gate facing east. The east gate — the direction of the rising sun, of Eden (Gen 2:8), of the glory that had departed (10:19; 11:23) — is now the gate of the returning presence. Matthew 24:27: 'As the lightning comes from the east and shines as far as the west, so will be the coming of the Son of Man.' The east gate is the gate of the Parousia; Ezekiel stands at the entrance of the event for which all history yearns.</p>",
        "2": "<p>'And behold, the glory of the God of Israel was coming from the east. And the sound of his coming was like the sound of many waters, and the earth shone with his glory.' The returning glory from the east, with a voice like many waters — and the earth shining with his glory. In Revelation, John sees one like a Son of Man whose voice is 'like the roar of many waters' (Rev 1:15). The same voice-description from Ezekiel's glory-vision is given to the enthroned Christ. The earth shining with his glory points to Rev 21:23-24: 'the city has no need of sun or moon ... for the glory of God gives it light, and its lamp is the Lamb.'</p>",
        "3": "<p>The vision matches the vision by the Chebar canal and the vision when he came to destroy the city. Ezekiel's visions form a unified series: Merkabah at Chebar (ch. 1), judgment on Jerusalem (ch. 9-10), return of the glory here (ch. 43). The same divine chariot that carried the glory away now carries it back. Revelation 4-5 recasts the Merkabah vision with the Lamb at its center: the one who received the seven-sealed scroll from the Ancient of Days is the returned glory in its NT form — Christ enthroned above the four living creatures.</p>",
        "4": "<p>'As the glory of the LORD entered the temple by the gate facing east...' The glory enters through the east gate, permanently consecrating it. Ezekiel 44:2 will specify that this gate is to be shut permanently because 'the LORD, the God of Israel, has entered by it.' Jesus enters Jerusalem from the east through the Golden Gate (Matt 21:1-11); the traditional identification of this as the Messiah's entry gate is rooted in Ezekiel 43:4. The gate through which Christ entered — his incarnation, his passion, his resurrection — is uniquely his: the door marked with his return, held open for his parousia.</p>",
        "5": "<p>'And the Spirit lifted me up and brought me into the inner court, and behold, the glory of the LORD filled the temple.' The Spirit carries the prophet to witness the moment of filling. John 1:14: 'And the Word became flesh and dwelt among us, and we have seen his glory, glory as of the only Son from the Father, full of grace and truth.' The incarnation is the new filling of the temple with glory — what the cloud did for the tabernacle (Exod 40:34-35) and for Solomon's temple (1 Kgs 8:10-11), Christ's body does permanently. The Spirit who lifts Ezekiel to witness the filling is the same Spirit who overshadowed Mary and filled the new temple at conception (Luke 1:35).</p>",
        "6": "<p>'While the man was standing beside me, I heard one speaking to me out of the temple.' Two figures: the angelic guide who stands beside the prophet and the divine voice from within the filled temple. The double-figure pattern throughout this vision anticipates the incarnate mediation of Christ: visible human figure alongside the speaking divine presence. In Jesus both figures collapse into one — the man who stands beside us IS the voice that speaks from the Father's fullness (John 1:18: 'the only God, who is at the Father's side, he has made him known').</p>",
        "7": "<p>'This is the place of my throne and the place of the soles of my feet, where I will dwell in the midst of the people of Israel forever.' The divine declaration: my throne, my footstool, my permanent dwelling. 'Son of man' addressed to Ezekiel is the title Jesus claims for himself from Daniel 7:13, signaling he is the one who inherits this throne. Revelation 3:21: 'The one who conquers, I will grant to sit with me on my throne.' The throne's permanent dwelling among the people is Rev 21:3: 'Behold, the dwelling place of God is with man. He will dwell with them, and they will be his people.'</p>",
        "8": "<p>Israel's kings had profaned the sanctuary by placing their thresholds beside YHWH's threshold, their doorposts beside his doorposts, only a wall between them. Human royal pretension crowding the divine king's space. Christ makes no such pretension — he does not grasp at equality with God (Phil 2:6) but empties himself, and is therefore given the Name above every name. His humility removes the wall between human and divine: he does not crowd the Father's threshold but IS the threshold ('I am the door', John 10:9), and in him the two thresholds are united in one person without confusion.</p>",
        "9": "<p>'Now let them put away their whoredom and the corpses of their kings far from me, and I will dwell in their midst forever.' Permanent indwelling conditioned on idolatry's removal. Christ accomplishes the removal: 'by canceling the record of debt that stood against us with its legal demands ... he disarmed the rulers and authorities and put them to open shame' (Col 2:14-15). The idols that blocked YHWH's permanent dwelling are stripped away at the cross. The new covenant promise ('I will never leave you nor forsake you', Heb 13:5) is unconditional precisely because Christ has already met the condition — the idols have been put away.</p>",
        "10": "<p>'Son of man, describe to the house of Israel the temple, that they may be ashamed of their iniquities, and let them measure the plan.' The vision of the perfect sanctuary is shown to produce shame and repentance. John 12:32: 'And I, when I am lifted up from the earth, will draw all people to myself.' The display of the true temple — Christ crucified — simultaneously shames human sin and draws sinners to God. Hebrews 12:2: 'looking to Jesus, the founder and perfecter of our faith, who for the joy that was set before him endured the cross, despising the shame.' The measuring of the plan is the measuring of Christ's person and work.</p>",
        "11": "<p>'And if they are ashamed of all that they have done, make known to them the plan of the temple ... that they may observe all its laws and all its statutes and carry them out.' Shame precedes instruction; repentance opens the door to knowing the design. In Christ: 'I will put my laws into their minds and write them on their hearts' (Heb 8:10). The shameful seeing of the cross (v. 10) leads to the heart-writing of the law (v. 11) — the exact sequence of new covenant transformation. The architectural plan becomes the new-covenant ordinances written not on walls but within.</p>",
        "12": "<p>'This is the law of the temple: the whole territory on top of the mountain all around shall be most holy. Behold, this is the law of the temple.' The entire holy mountain is the most holy place. Hebrews 12:22: 'You have come to Mount Zion and to the city of the living God, the heavenly Jerusalem.' In Christ, the 'law of the temple' is extended from the inner chamber to the entire mountain — and in the new creation, from the mountain to the whole cosmos. 1 Corinthians 6:19-20: 'Your body is a temple of the Holy Spirit ... glorify God in your body.' The believer is the most holy zone, because Christ's Spirit dwells within.</p>",
        "13": "<p>The altar measurements begin: the base, the ledge, the standard cubit. The altar is the place where God and his people meet through sacrifice. In Christ, the altar is his cross. The precise architectural specifications say: this meeting was exactly planned — not improvised, not accidental. Hebrews 9:22: 'Without the shedding of blood there is no forgiveness of sins.' The altar's careful dimensions enforce the doctrine that atonement is structurally necessary, not optional, and Christ's cross is its perfectly measured fulfillment.</p>",
        "14": "<p>The lower and upper settles (ledges) of the altar — 2 cubits to the first ledge, then 4 cubits to the greater settle. The layered structure of the altar = layered access. The Mosaic sacrificial system had graduated levels of approach: Levites, priests, high priest. Christ collapses all layers into one: 'through him we both have access in one Spirit to the Father' (Eph 2:18). The two levels of the altar — lower settle and greater settle — are unified in the one sacrifice of Christ who descends to our depth (incarnation) and ascends to the highest ledge (ascension).</p>",
        "15": "<p>The altar hearth (אריאל, <em>Ariel</em>), 4 cubits tall with 4 horns at its corners. Ariel means 'lion of God' and is also a poetic name for Jerusalem (Isa 29:1). Four horns at four corners = the universal reach of the sacrifice. The four altar horns were the points where blood was applied (Exod 29:12) and where fugitives could take refuge (1 Kgs 1:50): they declare both atonement and asylum. At Christ's cross-altar, blood is applied to the four corners of the cosmos and every fugitive from divine justice finds asylum: 'we have fled for refuge to lay hold on the hope set before us' (Heb 6:18).</p>",
        "16": "<p>The altar hearth is 12 cubits square. Twelve = the tribes of Israel and the apostles of Christ. The twelve-square altar encompasses the full people of God: the OT twelve tribes and the NT twelve apostles who together constitute the walls and foundations of the new Jerusalem (Rev 21:12-14). The sacrifice offered on this altar is for all twelve — for the full number of the redeemed drawn from every direction of the compass.</p>",
        "17": "<p>The ledge is 14 cubits square, with a border of half a cubit and a base of one cubit, with steps facing east. Fourteen is twice seven — the number of completeness doubled. Matthew's genealogy organizes history into three sets of fourteen generations (3 × 14 = 42) leading to Jesus (Matt 1:17). The fourteen-cubit ledge carries the numerological signature of the Christ who arrives at the end of the seven-fold genealogical fullness. The steps face east — ascent toward the altar is oriented toward the coming glory.</p>",
        "18": "<p>'These are the ordinances for the altar: On the day when it is erected for offering burnt offerings upon it and for throwing blood against it.' The day of altar dedication — the day the altar comes into its proper use. The cross is the day of the true altar's definitive dedication: the once-for-all sacrifice that ends all prior dedications. Hebrews 10:10: 'We have been sanctified through the offering of the body of Jesus Christ once for all.' The day of dedication is finished; the altar is permanently consecrated; the sacrifice needs no repetition.</p>",
        "19": "<p>'You shall give to the Levitical priests of the family of Zadok, who draw near to me to minister to me, a bull from the herd for a sin offering.' The Zadokite priests offer the sin-offering bull. Zadok means 'righteous.' The true Zadokite — the righteous one who ministers before the LORD — is Christ: Acts 3:14 calls him 'the Holy and Righteous One'; 1 John 2:1 names him 'Jesus Christ the righteous' as our advocate. He is from the order of Melchizedek ('king of righteousness,' Heb 7:2), a greater priestly house than even Zadok, and he offers not a bull but himself — the sin offering that ends all sin offerings.</p>",
        "20": "<p>'You shall take some of its blood and put it on the four horns of the altar, and on the four corners of the ledge, and upon the rim all around.' Blood applied to four horns, four corners, and the entire rim. The blood of Christ reaches every corner: Revelation 7:9 sees a great multitude from 'every nation, tribe, people, and language' — the four-corner blood-application read as the four-cornered universality of the atonement. The rim of the altar is the horizon of the gospel: 'to the end of the earth' (Acts 1:8). Blood on every edge means atonement available at every extremity.</p>",
        "21": "<p>'You shall also take the bull of the sin offering, and it shall be burned in the appointed place belonging to the temple, outside the sanctuary.' Burned outside the sanctuary. This is the explicit type that Hebrews identifies as fulfilled at the crucifixion: 'For the bodies of those animals whose blood is brought into the holy places by the high priest as a sacrifice for sin are burned outside the camp. So Jesus also suffered outside the gate in order to sanctify the people through his own blood' (Heb 13:11-12). Christ was crucified outside Jerusalem's gate — the definitive sin-offering burned outside the sanctuary, making the people holy through his blood shed in the profane space.</p>",
        "22": "<p>'On the second day you shall offer a male goat without blemish for a sin offering.' The second day's sin offering. The sevenfold pattern of altar consecration continues — the ongoing purification of the altar across the full week of inauguration. While the altar must be purified daily during its seven-day dedication, Christ's single sacrifice is permanently sufficient (Heb 10:14: 'by a single offering he has perfected for all time those who are being sanctified'). The church returns daily to Christ's one sacrifice not to add to it but to receive from it.</p>",
        "23": "<p>'When you have finished purifying it, you shall offer a young bull without blemish and a ram without blemish from the flock.' Completion of purification followed by the burnt offering. Hebrews 9:14: 'How much more will the blood of Christ, who through the eternal Spirit offered himself without blemish to God, purify our conscience from dead works to serve the living God.' The without-blemish requirement is the holiness standard that only Christ meets: his offering is without spot, his blood purifies not the altar but the conscience — the deeper sacrifice achieving the deeper purification.</p>",
        "24": "<p>'You shall present them before the LORD, and the priests shall throw salt on them and offer them up as a burnt offering to the LORD.' Salt on the offering — the salt of the covenant (Num 18:19; Lev 2:13). Mark 9:49-50: 'everyone will be salted with fire ... Have salt in yourselves, and be at peace with one another.' The covenant of salt is permanent and preserving. Christ's new covenant is 'a covenant of salt' — the salting of his sacrifice ratifies an everlasting bond between God and his people that neither party may dissolve.</p>",
        "25": "<p>'For seven days you shall provide daily a goat for a sin offering; also a young bull and a ram from the flock, without blemish, shall be provided.' Seven days of daily sin and burnt offerings. The seven-day altar consecration mirrors the seven-day ordination of the Aaronic priests (Lev 8:33-36). The seven days of the Passion Week — from Palm Sunday's entry through the Sabbath rest in the tomb — are the seven days of Christ's priestly self-consecration. As the Aaronic priest spent seven days in the tent of meeting before beginning his ministry (Lev 8:35), Christ spent seven days of culminating obedience before completing his once-for-all sacrifice.</p>",
        "26": "<p>'Seven days shall they make atonement for the altar and cleanse it, and so consecrate it.' Seven days of atonement, cleansing, and consecration — and then the altar is fully consecrated. Seven = completeness; the seven-day completion of the Passion Week ends with the Sabbath, the day of completed work. Christ 'finished the work' (John 17:4) and on the seventh day rested in the tomb — 'It is finished' (John 19:30) is the declaration that the seven days of atonement-and-consecration are complete.</p>",
        "27": "<p>'And when they have completed these days, then from the eighth day onward the priests shall offer on the altar your burnt offerings and your peace offerings, and I will accept you, declares the Lord GOD.' The eighth day — the new beginning after the completed seven. The resurrection is the eighth day: Sunday is both the first day of the new creation week and the eighth day after the previous Sunday of triumphal entry, the day that breaks the cycle of the old week and inaugurates the perpetual new. 'I will accept you' — the Father's acceptance of the risen and glorified Christ is the ground of his acceptance of all who are in Christ: 'To the praise of his glorious grace, with which he has blessed us in the Beloved' (Eph 1:6). The peace offerings of the eighth day are Christ risen, saying 'Peace be with you' (John 20:19, 21, 26) to his priestly people gathered in the new temple.</p>"
    }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'ezekiel')
    merge_comm(existing, EZEKIEL_CHRIST)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'ezekiel', existing)
    for ch in ['41', '42', '43']:
        vv = existing.get(ch, {})
        print(f'  ch{ch}: {len(vv)} verse(s) with christ commentary')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
